""""If I had invested..." — Indian stock time-machine logic.

Answers a single question: if you had put a lump sum into an Indian stock or
index at the end of year Y, what would it be worth today?

The math is a one-liner (value = amount x now_price / start_price); the value of
this module is the *data* baked into ``_PAYLOAD`` below. Those are year-end
**adjusted** closing prices from Yahoo Finance, i.e. already corrected for
stock splits, bonus issues and dividends. Because Yahoo back-adjusts the whole
history each time a dividend is paid, the ratio now/then is a **total-return**
figure: it assumes dividends were reinvested. All prices are in INR.

The data is a static snapshot taken on the date in ``AS_OF`` -- this is a
static site with no backend, so prices do not update live. Treat the output as
an illustration of past performance, not a live quote or investment advice.

Refresh the snapshot by re-running the fetch script that produced ``_PAYLOAD``
(year-end = last monthly adjusted close of each calendar year; the current,
partial year is dropped and the live ``now`` price is used for "today").
"""

